# Vibecodr Security Architecture

> **Last updated:** February 2026
>
> This document describes how Vibecodr protects your code, data, and secrets.
> It is written for users deploying code to our platform and is intentionally
> public. If you find a vulnerability, please email **founder@vibecodr.space**.

---

## Overview

Vibecodr has two primary runtime environments:

| Environment | What runs there | Where it executes |
|-------------|----------------|-------------------|
| **Vibes** | Client-side web apps (HTML/CSS/JS) | Sandboxed iframe in the viewer's browser |
| **Pulses** | Server-side functions (dedicated Cloudflare Workers) | Cloudflare's global edge network in isolated V8 runtimes |

Both environments are designed around a single principle: **your code cannot
access anyone else's code, data, or secrets — and vice versa.**

---

## 1. Authentication

Vibecodr uses [Clerk](https://clerk.com) for user authentication.

- **JWT-based** — Every authenticated API request carries a short-lived
  JSON Web Token verified via Clerk's JWKS endpoint.
- **Signature verification** — Tokens are verified using RS256 public key
  cryptography. The API worker fetches and caches signing keys from Clerk's
  JWKS endpoint and validates every token's signature, issuer, audience,
  and expiration before granting access.
- **Role-based access** — Admin and moderator endpoints require elevated
  roles embedded in JWT claims. Standard users cannot access administrative
  functions.
- **Suspension enforcement** — Write endpoints check suspension status.
  Suspended users enter read-only mode and cannot perform actions that affect
  other users.

### Pulse execution auth

All Pulse execution is gated by short-lived **pulse grant** tokens — signed
JWTs scoped to a specific Pulse ID with an expiration measured in minutes.

- **All Pulses** require a valid pulse grant token. The API worker issues
  grants after verifying the caller's identity via their Clerk JWT.
- **Private Pulses** additionally restrict execution to the Pulse owner.
  Non-owners receive a 403 even with a valid grant.
- **Public/unlisted Pulses** allow any authenticated user with a valid grant
  to execute them.

---

## 2. Vibes — Client-Side Sandbox

When you view or play a vibe in the browser, the code runs inside a
**sandboxed iframe** served from a **dedicated runtime domain** (`vxbe.space`)
that is completely separate from the main Vibecodr application. Each vibe gets
its own unique subdomain (e.g., `c-{id}-rt.vxbe.space`), so vibes are isolated
from each other and from the platform.

- **Cross-origin isolation** — The runtime domain (`vxbe.space`) is a
  separate origin from the Vibecodr application (`vibecodr.space`). Vibes
  cannot read cookies, session tokens, or any data belonging to the platform.
- **Per-vibe subdomains** — Each vibe runs on its own subdomain, so
  localStorage and other origin-scoped APIs are isolated between vibes.
- **No access to platform secrets** — The sandbox is completely isolated from
  the authenticated session.
- **Communication via postMessage only** — The iframe can only communicate
  with the host through a controlled handshake-based message protocol with
  session secret verification.
- **Content Security Policy (CSP)** — Each vibe is served with a strict CSP
  that controls what resources can be loaded:
  - Scripts can load from HTTPS CDNs (esm.sh, unpkg, cdnjs, etc.)
  - Connections limited to HTTPS and WSS protocols
  - No access to platform infrastructure or internal endpoints
- **Network egress from the viewer's browser** — Outbound requests from vibes
  go directly from the viewer's browser, not through Vibecodr infrastructure.

### Code safety

- Published vibe bundles are checked against a **code hash blocklist** to
  prevent known-malicious content from being served.
- User-uploaded files (SVG, HTML, XML) are served with security headers
  (`script-src 'none'`, `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`) that prevent
  embedded scripts from executing outside the sandbox.

---

## 3. Pulses — Server-Side Isolation

Each Pulse is a **dedicated Cloudflare Worker** deployed via
[Workers for Platforms (WfP)](https://developers.cloudflare.com/cloudflare-for-platforms/workers-for-platforms/).
This is not a shared container — each Pulse gets its own isolated runtime.

### V8 isolate separation

- Every Pulse executes in a **dedicated V8 isolate** with its own memory heap.
- **No shared memory** between isolates — one Pulse physically cannot read
  another Pulse's variables, data, or execution state.
- **CPU time limits** enforced by the Cloudflare Workers runtime.
- **No filesystem access** — Workers are stateless by design.
- When a Pulse finishes executing, its isolate state is cleaned up.

### Trust boundary

A **Dispatch Worker** acts as a security gatekeeper between incoming requests
and your Pulse:

```
Request → Dispatch (trusted, platform-controlled)
            ↓
          Auth check → Rate limit check → Quota check
            ↓
          User Worker (your code, untrusted, isolated)
```

Your Pulse code never has direct access to platform databases, other users'
data, or infrastructure secrets. The Dispatch Worker controls exactly what
context your code receives.

### SSRF protection

When your Pulse makes outbound HTTP requests, multiple layers of protection
prevent Server-Side Request Forgery:

- **Infrastructure blocklist** — Requests to internal infrastructure
  hostnames and cloud metadata endpoints are blocked.
- **Private IP blocking** — Requests to localhost, link-local, and private
  IP ranges are blocked. Cloudflare Workers also have no internal network
  access by design — private IPs aren't routable from the edge.
- **Redirect re-validation** — If an upstream server redirects your request,
  the new destination is re-checked against the blocklist before following.
- **Request tagging** — All outbound requests from Pulses are tagged for
  observability.

---

## 4. Secrets Management

Secrets (API keys, tokens, credentials) are handled with a **zero-exposure
architecture**:

- **Encrypted at rest** — All secrets are encrypted using AES-256-GCM before
  storage. Encryption keys are managed separately from the database.
- **Key rotation support** — Encryption keys can be rotated without
  re-encrypting all secrets at once. The system tries the newest key first,
  then falls back to the previous key.
- **Secrets never enter user code memory** — When your Pulse needs to use a
  secret (e.g., to call an external API), the Dispatch Worker:
  1. Decrypts the secret server-side
  2. Injects it into the outbound request (URL, headers, or body)
  3. Makes the upstream request on your behalf
  4. **Redacts** the secret value from the upstream response before returning
     it to your code
- **Scoped per Pulse and per user** — Secrets can be stored at the Pulse
  level or at the user level. Pulse-level secrets take priority; user-level
  secrets act as a shared baseline across your Pulses. Secrets belonging to
  other users are never accessible.
- **Platform secrets isolated** — Infrastructure credentials (API tokens, JWT
  signing keys, etc.) are never exposed to user code.

### OAuth connections

For OAuth-based integrations, tokens are encrypted with a separate key and
follow the same zero-exposure pattern. Token refresh is handled server-side
by the Dispatch Worker.

---

## 5. Data Isolation

### KV storage

Every Pulse gets its own key-value namespace. Keys are automatically prefixed
with the Pulse ID, so `env.kv.put("mykey", value)` stores to an
isolated namespace. One Pulse cannot read or write another Pulse's keys.

### D1 database (Pro)

Pro users receive a **dedicated Cloudflare D1 database instance** — not a
shared database with row-level filtering, but a physically separate database.
Your tables exist only in your database, providing infrastructure-level
isolation.

### R2 file storage

User-uploaded assets (avatars, covers, capsule files) are stored in
Cloudflare R2. Paid users receive per-user storage buckets. All file access
is authenticated and scoped to the owning user.

---

## 6. Rate Limiting & Abuse Prevention

Multiple layers protect the platform from abuse:

- **Per-user rate limiting** — Sliding window counters limit request
  frequency per user and per Pulse.
- **Daily request caps** — Plan-specific daily limits prevent runaway usage.
- **CPU budget tracking** — Wall-clock execution time is tracked per Pulse
  to prevent resource abuse (e.g., crypto mining).
- **Concurrency limits** — Per-Pulse and per-owner concurrency caps prevent
  a single user from monopolizing compute resources.
- **Auto-quarantine** — Pulses that repeatedly fail or exceed limits can be
  automatically disabled to protect both the user's quota and the platform.
- **Fail-closed for security-critical paths** — If the concurrency guard
  or secrets infrastructure is unavailable, requests are denied rather than
  allowed through.

---

## 7. Content Security Policy (CSP)

### Vibes (client-side)

Vibe bundles are served with a CSP that balances creator freedom with safety:

- `default-src 'none'` — Nothing allowed unless explicitly permitted
- `script-src` — Self, blob (for Web Workers), and HTTPS CDNs
- `connect-src` — Self, HTTPS, and WSS (for public APIs and WebSockets)
- `img-src`, `font-src`, `media-src` — Self, data URIs, blob, and HTTPS
- `frame-ancestors 'none'` — Vibes cannot be embedded in third-party iframes
- `form-action 'none'` — Forms cannot submit to external URLs
- CSP violation reports are collected for monitoring

### User-uploaded files

Files served from storage that could contain executable content (HTML, SVG,
XML) receive a restrictive CSP:

- `script-src 'none'` — No script execution permitted
- `object-src 'none'` — No plugin content
- `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff` — Prevents MIME-type sniffing attacks

---

## 8. CORS Policy

The API enforces strict Cross-Origin Resource Sharing:

- **Origin allowlist** — Only first-party origins are permitted for
  authenticated requests. The allowlist is maintained server-side and cannot
  be bypassed by client-side configuration.
- **Tiered policies** — Different endpoint categories (public read, 
  authenticated write, Pulse execution, storage management) each have their
  own origin allowlist with the minimum necessary permissions.
- **Credentials required** — Authenticated endpoints require
  `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` and only respond to allowlisted origins.
- **Localhost access** — Development origins (localhost) are only permitted
  when the API is running in development mode.

---

## 9. Data Durability

- **Write-ahead journaling** — Critical data (runtime events, engagement
  metrics) is persisted to durable storage before acknowledgment to the
  client.
- **Automatic recovery** — If a Durable Object is evicted or restarts, it
  rehydrates from its journal on startup.
- **Retry with backoff** — Failed database writes are automatically retried.
- **Analytics backup** — Runtime events are additionally written to
  Cloudflare Analytics Engine for long-term retention.

---

## 10. Infrastructure

| Layer | Technology |
|-------|-----------|
| **Frontend hosting** | Cloudflare Pages |
| **API** | Cloudflare Workers |
| **Pulse runtime** | Cloudflare Workers for Platforms (V8 isolates) |
| **Database** | Cloudflare D1 (SQLite at the edge) |
| **File storage** | Cloudflare R2 (S3-compatible object storage) |
| **Key-value** | Cloudflare KV |
| **Durable state** | Cloudflare Durable Objects |
| **Analytics** | Cloudflare Analytics Engine |
| **Authentication** | Clerk (JWKS-based JWT verification) |
| **DNS & CDN** | Cloudflare |

All infrastructure runs on Cloudflare's global network. There are no
self-managed servers, VMs, or containers. This eliminates entire classes of
vulnerabilities (OS patching, container escapes, SSH access, etc.).

---

## 11. What We Don't Do

- **We don't store passwords** — Authentication is delegated to Clerk.
- **We don't log secrets** — Secret values are never written to logs or
  analytics.
- **We don't share data between users** — Isolation is enforced at every
  layer.
- **We don't allow platform access from user code** — User Workers cannot
  reach platform databases, internal APIs, or infrastructure credentials.
- **Security-critical paths fail closed** — When concurrency, secrets, or
  host allowlist infrastructure is unavailable, requests are denied.

---

## Reporting Vulnerabilities

If you discover a security vulnerability, please report it responsibly:

**Email:** founder@vibecodr.space

We take all reports seriously and will respond as quickly as possible. Please
do not publicly disclose vulnerabilities before we've had a chance to address
them.

---

*This document describes the security architecture as of February 2026.
We continuously improve our security posture and will update this document
as the architecture evolves.*
